@laststand6420 Fission is just as bad. The last new US Nuclear plant Vogtle, GA (still under construction, but started in 2004) cost $32B for 2GWe.  It takes 20 years to build a new plant.

Second Used & Spent fuel require 4 years of active cooling, If the grid fails for more than a couple of weeks they turn into doomsday machine making continents uninhabitable for thousands of years. If the US gets hit with a major CME, or EMP, its the end of North America. The US still doesn't even have a long term storage for spent fuel. Its all sitting on site, even at the decommissioned plants.

Third the World is running out of economically recoverable Uranium. Global product peaked in 1980 and has been in decline since. Economically recoverable Uranium will be gone around 2050-2070. So if you start a new plant today, it would be operational until about 2045. It takes about 40 to 50 years to break even on CapEx costs.

