@arunjohnson1162 I saw a presentation at the ICCF conference about it long ago, and a quick google scholar search of "heavy fermion" or "heavy quasiparticle" "catalyzed LENR" pulls up a handful of results. Lots of articles were taken down: not sure whether this was because the concept wasn't viable, or because it went dark.  I see Kalinowski's paper is still up at the moment.

One important caveat is you need a layered material or a material with nano-cracks to confine the heavy fermions spatially, otherwise they are too diffuse (~1 micron across!) to actually catalyze anything
Also most heavy fermion materials have heavy fermions at low temperatures, so you may need to pump materials with optical or infrared light to produce quasiparticle excitations at higher temperatures, as with optically pumped/photomolecular superconductivity.

@calvingreene90 Unfortunately Nuclear power is a dead end. There is only enough economically recoverable uranium to run existing fission plants until about 2050. 
No way will Thorium or fusion be the solution. Thorium is very expensive & we still don't have a working reactor (thorim breeder) design and U-232 (by product) is a major problem. Thorium is not a fissile material and needs to be converted to U233 to power the reactor. Breeder reactors are extremely expensive and every nation that built them, ended up shutting them down do never ending problems and very high costs.

Fusion is the stuff of sci-fi, but not possible in reality.
